  "final_answer": "Both tests pass. Here's what was wrong and what I fixed:\n\n**Original `counter.py`:**\n\n```python\ndef count_words(text):\n    return len(text)         # ❌ counts characters, e.g. \"hello world\" → 11\n```\n\n**Fixed:**\n\n```python\ndef count_words(text):\n    return len(text.split()) # ✅ splits on whitespace, e.g. \"hello world\" → 2\n```\n\n- `str.split()` with no argument splits on any whitespace and discards empty strings, which is the standard \"word counting\" behavior.\n- `summarize` was already returning `{\"words\": count_words(text)}` — the correct shape — so it just needed `count_words` to work properly.",
